78
00:02:41,113 --> 00:02:46,454
So back in the mid-2000s, my co-founders and I had played a ton of Diablo II,

79
00:02:46,734 --> 00:02:48,655
like thousands and thousands and thousands of hours.

80
00:02:49,035 --> 00:02:53,356
And as we, over time, tired of the game, we looked at other action RPGs that we wanted to try out.

81
00:02:53,376 --> 00:02:55,877
You know, we tried out Dungeon Siege series and Titan Quest and so on.

82
00:02:56,297 --> 00:02:58,118
And we played those games too and enjoyed them,

83
00:02:58,458 --> 00:03:01,279
but only for dozens of hours rather than thousands of hours.

84
00:03:01,599 --> 00:03:05,220
And so this caused us to ask, why did we sink so much more time into Diablo II?

85
00:03:05,260 --> 00:03:06,020
What was perfect?

86
00:03:06,060 --> 00:03:08,621
What made that game the best action RPG that had ever existed?

87
00:03:09,141 --> 00:03:13,285
And so we came up with a bunch of design pillars that we feel a perfect action RPG needs that some

88
00:03:13,305 --> 00:03:18,289
of the other games hadn't quite hit in all cases. And so those design pillars are as follows.

89
00:03:19,132 --> 00:03:21,054
The first one is visceral action combat.

90
00:03:21,074 --> 00:03:22,855
This goes without saying, it's an action RPG.

91
00:03:22,875 --> 00:03:23,956
You need to have immediacy.

92
00:03:23,976 --> 00:03:25,538
You hit a monster, it dies.

93
00:03:25,598 --> 00:03:26,378
Blood goes everywhere.

94
00:03:26,438 --> 00:03:29,141
It falls back, and it's nice and fast and action-based.

95
00:03:29,401 --> 00:03:30,622
And you have to remember, back in 2006,

96
00:03:31,943 --> 00:03:33,344
the atmosphere of online games,

97
00:03:33,364 --> 00:03:35,686
like the climate they were in was World of Warcraft clones.

98
00:03:36,106 --> 00:03:38,088
The way combat worked is you walk up to a monster

99
00:03:38,488 --> 00:03:39,189
and you target it,

100
00:03:39,229 --> 00:03:40,970
and then your character starts hitting it on a timer

101
00:03:41,010 --> 00:03:42,432
and you press your cooldowns occasionally,

102
00:03:42,472 --> 00:03:43,312
and there's no real action.

103
00:03:43,332 --> 00:03:44,994
You're not dodging out of the way when it attacks

104
00:03:45,014 --> 00:03:46,015
because it's gonna hit you anyway.

105
00:03:46,595 --> 00:03:50,358
And so nowadays, of course, everyone's doing a much better job at visceral action combat.

106
00:03:50,458 --> 00:03:52,861
Even strict MMOs that come out have great combat in them.

107
00:03:53,221 --> 00:03:55,843
Games like Black Desert Online, for example, feel really good to play.

108
00:03:56,103 --> 00:03:57,705
So that's a pillar that everyone understands.

109
00:03:57,725 --> 00:04:00,427
There's no particular secret that you need action in an action RPG.

110
00:04:01,444 --> 00:04:03,226
Second, we have randomly generated levels.

111
00:04:03,286 --> 00:04:05,047
Now this is secret sauce for sure.

112
00:04:05,127 --> 00:04:06,928
There were games like Titan Quest that came out

113
00:04:06,988 --> 00:04:08,830
where I played through it and said, this is amazing.

114
00:04:08,870 --> 00:04:10,011
This is the new game I'm gonna play.

115
00:04:10,151 --> 00:04:11,332
And I started my second play through

116
00:04:11,432 --> 00:04:12,753
and didn't get a quarter of the way through it

117
00:04:12,793 --> 00:04:14,754
because I played it before as far as I was concerned.

118
00:04:15,135 --> 00:04:17,316
And so random levels dramatically help people

119
00:04:17,356 --> 00:04:17,977
replay the game.

120
00:04:17,997 --> 00:04:19,198
And when you want a game to be played

121
00:04:19,238 --> 00:04:21,700
for 10 to 20,000 hours over the life cycle

122
00:04:21,720 --> 00:04:22,701
of some of your longest users,

123
00:04:23,081 --> 00:04:25,363
it needs to have the randomness that enables them

124
00:04:25,383 --> 00:04:26,904
to play each individual tile set

125
00:04:27,024 --> 00:04:28,025
two or three or 400 hours worth.

126
00:04:29,636 --> 00:04:30,117
of gameplay.

127
00:04:30,477 --> 00:04:34,202
And so I'll be talking a bunch more about random level generation later on in the talk.

128
00:04:34,262 --> 00:04:37,926
I understand that procedural generation got a bit of a bashing in the last few years because

129
00:04:37,966 --> 00:04:42,472
some games have not used it particularly well, but used carefully with a lot of good theming,

130
00:04:42,772 --> 00:04:43,513
it can work really well.

131
00:04:44,254 --> 00:04:45,775
So next we have randomly generated items.

132
00:04:45,835 --> 00:04:47,577
Now I kind of wanted to just do an items talk,

133
00:04:47,617 --> 00:04:49,018
like just focus on this one for an hour,

134
00:04:49,098 --> 00:04:50,799
and I think I could do a good job of that,

135
00:04:50,899 --> 00:04:53,281
but I'm gonna briefly say that if you get

136
00:04:53,301 --> 00:04:55,803
your random item system good, it makes your game replayable.

137
00:04:55,823 --> 00:04:57,885
And the reason why is because in these kind of games,

138
00:04:57,905 --> 00:04:59,506
your items are your progress, right?

139
00:04:59,526 --> 00:05:01,167
The character level number doesn't matter so much.

140
00:05:01,228 --> 00:05:03,569
No one really cares if you got to level 97 or 94.

141
00:05:03,830 --> 00:05:05,631
What they care about is the cool items you found out

142
00:05:05,911 --> 00:05:06,672
that you got on the way.

143
00:05:07,052 --> 00:05:08,954
And the other nice thing about randomly generated items

144
00:05:09,014 --> 00:05:10,495
is it's not just a linear progression

145
00:05:10,515 --> 00:05:12,296
where the player knows they've got three items left to go

146
00:05:12,336 --> 00:05:12,977
and then they're finished.

147
00:05:13,457 --> 00:05:18,079
We're dealing with ones where the stats are all over the place, who knows what the next best item is, how far it can be pushed.

148
00:05:18,379 --> 00:05:23,001
And because of that you get this cool diminishing returns, so that players really appreciate the small upgrades they find.

149
00:05:23,041 --> 00:05:27,162
Because it's a 1% power increase for their character, but it makes them so much better than more of their friends.

150
00:05:28,083 --> 00:05:29,923
The next one is a secure online economy.

151
00:05:29,963 --> 00:05:33,305
Now this is one of the things that sounds obvious, clearly games need a secure online economy.

152
00:05:33,545 --> 00:05:35,926
But if it's obvious, why does everyone screw it up so badly?

153
00:05:36,226 --> 00:05:39,408
Like, the first thing is, so many games these days just remove trade.

154
00:05:39,468 --> 00:05:42,330
They're like, oh, there's gold sellers, we can't deal with that, we're just gonna get rid of trade.

155
00:05:42,530 --> 00:05:43,591
This is not the right direction.

156
00:05:43,651 --> 00:05:47,573
You need to have trade in your games that are about items, because that way the items have some value.

157
00:05:47,873 --> 00:05:50,475
If you find an item, and you're the only person that can ever consume that,

158
00:05:50,755 --> 00:05:53,757
it's not really something that you've achieved that you can actually, like...

159
00:05:54,537 --> 00:05:56,158
feel good about having, it doesn't have any weight to it.

160
00:05:56,699 --> 00:05:59,240
If you get a game where you get an item that you could give to your friends

161
00:05:59,480 --> 00:06:02,422
if you wanted to, but you're not going to because it's your item, but you could give it to them,

162
00:06:02,662 --> 00:06:04,003
that's something you feel good about having.

163
00:06:04,363 --> 00:06:07,165
And the ability for the item to actually transact with other players

164
00:06:07,485 --> 00:06:11,308
is a critical part in that item having worth in the economy and representing your accomplishment.

165
00:06:11,868 --> 00:06:15,790
The second part of this is the secure part, which again sounds obvious, but so many games these days,

166
00:06:16,410 --> 00:06:20,672
often from console developers who aren't used to proper secure client or server authoritative code,

167
00:06:21,172 --> 00:06:24,373
write their games in such a way that it's really easy to exploit them, there's dupe methods,

168
00:06:24,393 --> 00:06:27,095
there's various dumb stuff that goes on with the PC versions, you know, there's...

169
00:06:28,387 --> 00:06:34,389
There's a lot of horror stories there, but the key takeaway is that there are very few games that actually respect items to the degree that we try to.

170
00:06:34,450 --> 00:06:37,311
We want to make sure this is an online economy where the items are sacrosanct.

171
00:06:37,351 --> 00:06:39,092
They are the progress of the players. They're going to matter.

172
00:06:39,352 --> 00:06:41,933
We don't invalidate them too quickly with new releases of content.

173
00:06:42,513 --> 00:06:45,995
It's a big rant that you can tell I feel passionately about, but needless to say, get your items right.

174
00:06:46,495 --> 00:06:48,916
Anyway, the final one is deep character customization.

175
00:06:49,176 --> 00:06:52,618
This is merely the fact that if you have thousands and thousands of ways of playing your game,

176
00:06:52,638 --> 00:06:55,679
then when someone comes back to play it the second, third, fifth time,

177
00:06:55,939 --> 00:06:57,420
they have a different way that they can play it.

178
00:06:57,860 --> 00:07:00,521
And in some games where they just have a few simple character classes,

179
00:07:00,561 --> 00:07:01,602
and it's pretty straightforward,

180
00:07:01,782 --> 00:07:04,343
you'll play it with the first class, then you'll play it with the second one, then the third,

181
00:07:04,383 --> 00:07:06,424
and eventually you run out of new classes you haven't tried.

182
00:07:06,764 --> 00:07:10,065
Path of Exile tries very hard to make sure the class doesn't actually matter that much,

183
00:07:10,465 --> 00:07:11,706
it's more about what you're doing with it.

184
00:07:12,526 --> 00:07:19,051
Anyway, so there's the Preach E5 design pillars, and we felt that many of those other games that were released failed in a few areas, right?

185
00:07:19,071 --> 00:07:22,693
They didn't have the secure servers, they didn't have the random levels, the items were bad, and so on and so on.

186
00:07:22,994 --> 00:07:26,977
Very fun games to play through, totally worth their money, but not something you can actually sink your 20s into.

187
00:07:28,103 --> 00:07:32,847
All right, so the next, yep, the next topic is,

188
00:07:33,307 --> 00:07:34,929
we wanted to run this as a games as a service.

189
00:07:34,969 --> 00:07:35,970
This is something we knew back in 2006,

190
00:07:36,570 --> 00:07:37,871
though we didn't know the buzzwords for it,

191
00:07:37,911 --> 00:07:39,753
but it was something where we looked at Diablo II

192
00:07:39,833 --> 00:07:41,855
and they had tens of thousands of people

193
00:07:41,915 --> 00:07:44,697
coming back per realm for each one of their ladder resets.

194
00:07:44,817 --> 00:07:46,599
People were excited to jump back into that game

195
00:07:46,819 --> 00:07:48,400
because of the fresh economy and keep playing,

196
00:07:48,500 --> 00:07:49,701
even though the game was not being

197
00:07:49,741 --> 00:07:51,162
substantially updated during that time.

198
00:07:51,202 --> 00:07:53,344
There was a single expansion, a few tiny balance patches.

199
00:07:53,965 --> 00:07:58,130
no real additions. So we felt if we update our game every week with new items, new

200
00:07:58,650 --> 00:08:04,157
Keystone passives, new skills, and we keep Path of Exile updated incredibly fast. How can we not grow? This was the plan

201
00:08:04,177 --> 00:08:06,119
I mean, this is you know, 12 years ago now that we're planning it

202
00:08:06,940 --> 00:08:12,307
And this analysis also helped make us realize that we'd be economically viable at 10,000 average concurrent users

203
00:08:12,367 --> 00:08:14,309
So that means if you sample a number of players online

204
00:08:14,669 --> 00:08:17,110
And if there's 10,000 on average, we'd be totally fine.

205
00:08:17,130 --> 00:08:18,831
We were running a skeleton crew out of New Zealand,

206
00:08:18,871 --> 00:08:20,012
very few people on the team.

207
00:08:20,332 --> 00:08:21,793
We paid for the game ourselves.

208
00:08:21,853 --> 00:08:23,393
We didn't have any investors or publishers

209
00:08:23,413 --> 00:08:24,514
and all that kind of stuff back then.

210
00:08:24,894 --> 00:08:27,175
And we felt 10,000 people is enough to generate

211
00:08:27,255 --> 00:08:29,396
from cosmetic microtransactions,

212
00:08:29,897 --> 00:08:31,377
enough people to generate enough money

213
00:08:31,417 --> 00:08:33,178
to pay for the game service, to pay for development,

214
00:08:33,198 --> 00:08:35,179
to pay for the costs, and then have some money

215
00:08:35,199 --> 00:08:36,920
left over for ourselves if the business goes well.

216
00:08:37,200 --> 00:08:38,141
And so that was our target.

217
00:08:38,181 --> 00:08:39,661
We were aiming low and we tried to hit it.

218
00:08:40,483 --> 00:08:43,464
So, we scaled up from a team of three friends in my garage

219
00:08:43,544 --> 00:08:45,224
to this motley crew of 18 guys.

220
00:08:45,244 --> 00:08:47,224
This is a terrible photo I got on Google Image Search.

221
00:08:48,165 --> 00:08:50,145
These are the initial part of Excel team

222
00:08:50,165 --> 00:08:51,165
that launched the open beta.

